<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Touts 'Comprehensive' Drug Plan  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore courted senior citizens
and Hispanics Monday, touting his plan for a ''real,
comprehensive'' prescription drug benefit as a stark contrast to
the proposals of rival George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll put the power of medical science back in the medicine
cabinets of our mothers and fathers,'' Gore said of his Medicare
benefits plan. ''It's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking in the suburb of Clayton at a town hall-style
meeting with senior citizens, also took on the big drug companies,
accusing them of ''price gouging.'' And he criticized the
Republicans' drug bill now pending in Congress, saying it was put
together by the drug companies and ''its only purpose is to serve
as an illusion or camouflage.''
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the vice president was House Democratic leader Dick
Gephardt of St. Louis, who said the cost of drugs could be a
decisive matter in both the presidential election and the fight for
control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a huge, huge issue to senior citizens,'' said Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have received more than $3 million from drug
manufacturers, while the Democrats have gotten just over $700,000,
Gore aides said campaign finance records showed.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal Gore has offered would provide a prescription drug
benefit under the Medicare program, with the government paying half
of the annual costs up to $5,000. Aides said it would extend
coverage to 40 million people at a cost of $255 billion over 10
years. Gore had explained details of the proposal earlier, but was
hammering hard at his plan in the battleground state of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   He said many senior citizens have to choose between buying drugs
or going without other necessities. ''We just should not be putting
our seniors in that position,'' he said. ''It's just not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore flew to San Diego to pitch the proposal to the
National Council of La Raza, an important Hispanic group. He said
Hispanics would benefit under the prescription plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said 2 million Hispanics would gain because the number
eligible for Medicare was expected to triple over the next 25
years. Further, Hispanics are more than twice as likely to lack
supplemental coverage for prescription drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm committed to a real prescription drug benefit for all
Hispanics who rely on Medicare,'' Gore said. ''Not one that tells
them to go beg the HMOs and the insurance companies for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the vice president would focus on the prescription
drug proposal and health care throughout the week, including in
separate appearances before two big teachers' unions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was addressing the National Council of La Raza on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking to Hispanic activists, Gore telephoned Mexican
President-elect Vicente Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a good, long conversation,'' Gore said. ''He asked for
the chance to have a meeting in Washington soon. I will look
forward to having that discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said Mexico's ruling party deserves credit for losing
''gracefully and well, without challenging or overturning the
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Sen. Bob Graham, a Florida Democrat, made a
Gore-arranged conference call to reporters to criticize Bush for
offering minimal details about what he would provide in financing
for prescription drug aid to senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the American people deserve to have a clear statement
by Governor Bush as to what he would propose to do,'' said Graham,
sometimes mentioned as a vice presidential possibility for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett said Bush has been
consistent in proposing to allocate $5 trillion over five years to
both save and strengthen Social Security and Medicare, also
providing prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also said Gore, as vice president, should have
spoken up much earlier if he thought the issue was so important.
</P>
<P>
   ''After eight years of failing to propose a solution, the vice
president is calling for reform,'' said Missouri Rep. James Talent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his plan would cover far more people than a more
modest bill backed in Congress by Republicans. He also said his
plan is best because it includes coverage under Medicare, while
Republicans rely on insurance companies to provide the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   At the Missouri campaign stop, 72-year-old Jacqueline Steele
Johnson said she spends $423 of her monthly $870 income on
prescription drugs. She said she eats macaroni and cheese every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used his appearance for spirited criticism of big drug
makers, the second straight week he has taken on a large and
unpopular industry. Gore spent much of last week bashing big oil
companies over the soaring price of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are price gouging and you are paying the bill,'' Gore
said of the drug makers. ''There's no other industry in America
that has profits nearly as high.''
</P>
<P>
   There was something of a vice presidential buzz surrounding
Gore's swing with Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't talked about that,'' Gephardt said when questioned.
''As Harry Truman once said, I don't answer iffy questions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
