<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Black Bears Targeted in Crowded NJ  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WANTAGE, N.J. (AP) -- William Kellner didn't see the animal
coming.
</P>
<P>
   He had just closed the barbecue grill on the back porch of his
vacation trailer when his son yelled ''Bear!'' The black bear was
right behind Kellner, towering over him, sniffing at the grill.
After he backed inside, the bear put its paws on the trailer's
sliding glass door and stared at Kellner's family until it fled at
the sound of pots and pans.
</P>
<P>
   ''It scared me,'' said Kellner, who said he and his 12-year-old
son are eager to take part in a bear hunt this fall, the state's
first in 29 years and one that is stirring controversy.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's Fish and Game Council scheduled the hunt for 175
bears to curb a burgeoning ursine population that is killing
livestock and breaking into homes and cars. In the state with the
highest population density in the country, with more than 1,000 per
square mile, bears walk through suburban yards and saunter along
roads. Experts say they were born and raised with people around.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're used to cutting across the back lawn, coming across
the driveway, checking out the garage for trash,'' said Bob
Eriksen, a biologist with the state Division of Fish and Wildlife.
''They don't avoid people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, when bear hunts were abandoned, black bears
numbered ''well below'' 100 in New Jersey, Eriksen said. Now more
than 1,000 roam 11 counties, especially in northern parts like
Wantage, about 75 miles from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   If you go far enough north, in Sussex County at the northwestern
tip of New Jersey, just about everyone has seen a bear in the past
few years and has a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   A cub broke into Susan Snover's car in Stillwater last week to
get at the Sugar Corn Pops in a shopping bag. Flossie Masker, 91,
looks out her front door to see bears cut through her yard,
sniffing at her car before heading to the open road. John Keenan
has a mother and two cubs who regularly bash his bird feeders for
food.
</P>
<P>
   ''They come in my back yard almost every day,'' said 17-year-old
Matt Walloga of Lake Shawnee.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Division of Fish and Wildlife handled 250 bear
complaints, Eriksen said. Last year there were 1,659, including 29
complaints of bears entering homes, 29 complaints of killing goat,
sheep and other livestock, 12 attacks of pet dogs and 46 bears who
were killed by cars.
</P>
<P>
   Yet residents and legislators aren't sure whether killing bears
is the right way to control them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just leave them alone,'' said Masker, who watches the bears
from her front door. ''As long as they don't do no damage, they're
nice to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate last week passed a bill that would postpone a
bear hunt for five years and instructs the state to come up with
another population control plan that could include sterilizing
females. The bill is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner said hunters have an obligation to reduce the number of
bears competing for food.
</P>
<P>
   ''They'll starve to death if you don't kill them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not true, Eriksen said. Northern New Jersey offers enough
vegetation and wildlife to satisfy many more bears, but the problem
is that the animals are living too close to the sprawling suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Eriksen went to Stillwater last week to help remove a cub who
had become trapped inside Snover's Ford Escort, tearing off the
rearview mirror and pounding the horn in a frantic attempt to get
loose. After the cub was freed, it ran up a tree with another cub
and their mother.
</P>
<P>
   ''They go up a tree as fast as a squirrel,'' Eriksen said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials tranquilized the mother bear and took her a
short distance away from her children, then pelted her with rubber
bullets and pepper spray and yelled at her to discourage her from
returning. The bear came back, as Eriksen knew she would, to
retrieve the cubs. He said the separation was hopefully punishment
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Bears are killed by wildlife officials if they're caught two or
three times wreaking havoc near homes. But many residents say
they've grown comfortable with the creatures. Walloga followed one
once from his Lake Shawnee yard into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just went and sat in the woods and just laid there and
looked at me,'' Walloga said.
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't as welcoming, and blame some residents for feeding
the bears, encouraging them to come closer and closer.
</P>
<P>
   Said Wantage resident Judy Phillips, ''I think it's going to
take a child getting mauled for someone to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Information on black bears:
http://www.bear.org/species/blackbear/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Fish and Game Council hunt policy:
http://www.state.nj.us/dep/fgw/cnclmsgc.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
