<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resort company doubles reward for missing American writer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) - Sandals Resorts has doubled the reward
for information about a New York travel writer who disappeared
while staying at one of its camps in Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   The company on Monday raised the payment to $50,000 for clues
about Claudia Kirschhoch, an editor at New York-based Frommer's
Travel Guides, who was reported missing on June 2. Kirschhoch was
staying at a Sandals resort in western Negril.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first reward announcements triggered almost 400 calls,''
Sandals chairman Gordon Stewart said in a statement from London.
''We hope the larger reward will generate more calls and perhaps
loosen a tongue or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirschhoch arrived in Jamaica on May 24 as part of a
Sandals-sponsored tour for travel writers that was to continue to
Cuba. When the Cuba leg was canceled because of visa problems and
all flights back to New York were booked, she opted to stay in
Negril. She was last seen May 27.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing police investigation into Kirschhoch's disappearance
has yielded few clues. Last week, an FBI team arrived in Jamaica to
aid local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Kirschhoch's parents, who have visited twice, said last week
that the reward, then $25,000, would be raised no further.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart, the Sandals chairman, ''called and asked if he
could raise it, and even though we said we wouldn't raise it again,
I didn't see how this could hurt,'' Fred Kirschhoch said during a
telephone interview from his home in Morristown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who also owns Air Jamaica and other businesses, has
helped keep the story in the public eye through his Jamaica
Observer newspaper, which has published Kirschhoch's picture
several times.
</P>
<P>
   He has also paid for helicopter searches of the area around
Negril and last week hired two private investigators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
