<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Giuliani's Dad Served Time  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The late father of law-and-order Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani served 18 months in prison for holding up a milkman at
gunpoint in the 1930s, The Village Voice reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Giuliani pleaded guilty to armed robbery in 1934, a
decade before his son was born, the weekly newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and an accomplice stopped milkman Harold Hall as he
entered an Upper East Side apartment building to collect customer
payments, pointed a gun at him and took $128.82 from his pocket,
the Voice reported in an excerpt from reporter Wayne Barrett's
upcoming book.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Mindel, a spokeswoman for the mayor, declined to comment
on the story. ''We haven't read it,'' she said. ''Don't read The
Village Voice.''
</P>
<P>
   A call to the state Department of Correctional Services seeking
confirmation of the report was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes in a difficult year for Rudolph Giuliani, who
dropped out of the Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton after
revealing he had prostate cancer and was separating from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, a former federal prosecutor, has built his career on a
reputation as a crime fighter, gaining national prominence as New
York's crime rates dropped sharply. Until recently, he rarely spoke
about his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor recalled his father's influence on him while speaking
about his cancer diagnosis in April. His father died of prostate
cancer in 1981 at age 73.
</P>
<P>
   ''It brings up very painful memories,'' the mayor said when he
was diagnosed. ''And, you know, I miss my father every day of my
life. And he's a very, very important reason for why I'm standing
here as the mayor of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Voice, after a police officer interrupted the
robbery, an indictment identified Harold Giuliani, then 26, as the
man who pressed a gun into Hall's abdomen. But the milkman later
changed his statement, saying Giuliani's accomplice wielded the
pistol, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
   One prosecutor, Louis Capozzoli, said in court that Hall had
been told to change his story when ''he was visited at about four
o'clock that morning by several people who threatened him,''
according to the Voice.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Giuliani, who told a judge his name was Joseph Starrett,
was initially charged with four felonies, and pleaded innocent, the
Voice reported. After Hall changed his statement, Giuliani was
allowed to plead guilty to just one felony, according to the paper.
He was sentenced to two to five years and released on parole after
a year and a half, the Voice said.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice said Harold Giuliani's criminal record is filed under
the name Joseph Starrett.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice story portrayed Giuliani's father as a hot-tempered
man who was quick to throw a punch and rarely held a legitimate
job. In the late 1940s, he began working as a bartender at a tavern
owned by his brother-in-law Leo D'Avanzo, the Voice reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice said D'Avanzo ran a loan-sharking and gambling
operation out of the bar. Harold Giuliani wielded a baseball bat to
collect debts owed to his brother-in-law, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani moved his family from Brooklyn to Long Island in 1951,
and left his bartending job in the late 1950s to become a school
custodian. He was eventually fired for failing to show up to work,
the Voice said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
