<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Verdict Won by State Senator Cut  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PAYNE, Ala. (AP) -- A judge Monday cut by two-thirds a state
senator's $15.2 million award in a lawsuit against an insurance
company that allegedly tried to dig up dirt on him.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Randall Cole ordered the judgment for state Sen.
Lowell Barron reduced to $5.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge said the lesser amount still will ''send a clear
message'' that invading an elected official's privacy ''is not
acceptable behavior in our political system.''
</P>
<P>
   Barron sued Alfa insurance in 1997, contending the company
invaded his privacy by hiring private investigators to look into
his background. He claimed the company sought the information to
get him to support an Alfa vice president for a seat on the Auburn
University board.
</P>
<P>
   In February, jurors awarded Barron more than $15 million in
punitive damages. Barron's attorney, Dee Miles, said the senator
would accept the reduced amount rather than seek a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Alfa was closed for the holiday Monday and company officials
could not be reached for comment. They can appeal to the Alabama
Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
