<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At long last, Revolutionary War veteran gets honorary headstone  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STAMFORD, N.Y. (AP) - One hundred sixty-two years after his
death, a Revolutionary War corporal is getting a veteran's
headstone.
</P>
<P>
   Through a quirk of fate and the efforts of the Daughters of the
American Revolution and the state Department of Veterans Affairs,
Theophilus Howard will soon have a new gravestone indicating that
he served honorably in his country's war for independence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1773, Howard participated in the Boston Tea Party, in which
colonists protested the British tax on tea imported to the
Colonies. And beginning in 1775, Howard spent six months as a
private in Cambridge, Mass., during the British occupation of
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1776, he joined again for a year and was stationed first
in Williamsburg, Mass., as a corporal, and was listed as a gunner
and a bombardier. He was transferred to Naddles Island, off the
Massachusetts coast. When he was scheduled to go to Rhode Island,
he hired a substitute to finish out his term.
</P>
<P>
   He died May 23, 1838, had 12 children, several of whom are
buried next to him and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of his remembrance began with a meeting in Seattle
between Don Howard, a direct descendant of Theophilus Howard, and
Peggy Power Gifford, a member of the General Peter Gansevoort
Chapter of DAR who was visiting her sister.
</P>
<P>
   The two women decided to spend the afternoon at a genealogy
library, which is a common activity for members of the DAR. Members
must trace their ancestry to qualify for membership in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''I struck up a conversation with a complete stranger about the
DAR,'' Gifford said. ''He began telling me about his ancestor who
was in the Revolutionary War and took part in the Boston Tea Party.
I couldn't believe it when he said the man was buried in
Stamford.''
</P>
<P>
   As the conversation progressed, Howard revealed that the grave
didn't indicate that Theophilus was a veteran. Gifford, who works
with Desert Shield/Storm veteran Chuck Greenfield to get VA markers
for other soldiers, offered to do the legwork and submit the
application to properly mark Theophilus' grave.
</P>
<P>
   Within 30 days, Greenfield will come to Stamford to place a new
veteran's marker at the foot of Theophilus' grave. He always gives
the veterans a fitting tribute by playing ''Taps.'' To date, he has
placed more than 100 markers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I take pride in doing something for our veterans, giving them
the honor they deserve,'' Gifford said. ''Patriotism is important
to me,'' she told The Daily Star of Oneonta. ''When I see a parade
and see the flag go by, I get tears in my eyes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
