<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, July 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Govt. Sworn in During Crisis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- An all-Fijian temporary government was sworn in Tuesday in
defiance of hostage takers who are holding 27 members of the ousted, Indian-led
government at gunpoint in parliament. Banking executive Laisenia Qarase became
prime minister in an appointment that provoked the anger of the hostage takers
who had demanded a role in naming any new government. Armed clashes late broke
out between Fiji's military and the hostage takers after a news conference by
rebel leader George Speight, who said he did not expect the new government to
rule for long.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Touts 'Comprehensive' Drug Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore courted senior citizens and
Hispanics Monday, touting his plan for a ''real, comprehensive'' prescription
drug benefit as a stark contrast to the proposals of rival George W. Bush. Gore,
speaking in the suburb of Clayton at a town hall-style meeting with senior
citizens, also took on the big drug companies, accusing them of ''price
gouging.'' And he criticized the Republicans' drug bill now pending in Congress,
saying it was put together by the drug companies and ''its only purpose is to
serve as an illusion or camouflage.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arafat Seeks Statehood by Sept. 13
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- , Yasser Arafat's government told Palestinians
on Monday to prepare for statehood by Sept. 13, even as Israel insisted anew
that independence must come only as part of a peace accord. The PLO Central
Council, the Palestinians' chief policymaking body, declared its
''determination'' to declare independence by that time, and called on the world
community to recognize statehood when it is declared, ''noting the natural and
historical right of our nation to establish a state.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge Paul G. Hatfield Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GREAT FALLS, Mont. (AP) -- Senior U.S. District Judge Paul G. Hatfield, a
former senator who in 1979 cast a deciding vote for the treaties that gave the
Panama Canal back to the Central American country, died Monday. He was 72.
Hatfield apparently suffered a heart attack at his home, the coroner said.
Appointed to the Senate in 1978 after the death of Sen. Lee Metcalf, a fellow
Montana Democrat, Hatfield served for only a year. Hatfield was among the last
of the undecideds on the Panama Canal issue, and he did not make up his mind to
vote for ratification until the last moment. The treaties, which were
passionately opposed by many Montanans, were ratified by a single vote.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Speaks With Barak, Arafat
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton talked on the phone Monday to alestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, but no decision has
been reached for a Camp David-style Mideast summit. After a recent round of
shuttle diplomacy by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Palestinians and
Israelis were reported as remaining far apart on crucial issues, including
whether Israel would withdraw from all territory it took in the 1967 Six-Day
War. Clinton is trying to assess whether the parties are close enough to bring
the leaders together, or whether further lower-level negotiations are needed,
White House spokesman P.J. Crowley said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NASA Denies Hacker Attack Danger
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- NASA officials denied reports Monday that a computer
hacker attack in 1997 endangered astronauts by disrupting communications with
the space shuttle Atlantis. The British Broadcasting Corp. had reported that
during a rendezvous with the Russian space station Mir, a hacker interfered with
communications and forced the shuttle crew to use the Russian station to
maintain contact with NASA. National Aeronautics and Space Administration
spokesman Bob Jacobs said ground controllers never lost contact with the
astronauts nor did they use the Russian space station as a communications relay.
</P>
