<HEADLINE> Revolutionary War Veteran Honored  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, N.Y. (AP) -- One hundred sixty-two years after his
death -- although not quite in time for Independence Day -- a
Revolutionary War corporal is getting a veteran's headstone.
</P>
<P>
   Through a quirk of fate and the efforts of the Daughters of the
American Revolution and the state Department of Veterans Affairs,
Theophilus Howard will soon have a new gravestone indicating he
served honorably in the war for independence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1773, Howard participated in the Boston Tea Party, a protest
of the British tax on tea imported to the Colonies. And beginning
in 1775, Howard spent six months as a private in Cambridge, Mass.,
during the British occupation of Boston. He died May 23, 1838.
</P>
<P>
   The new headstone was arranged when Don Howard, one of
Theophilus' direct descendants, met New York DAR member Peggy Power
Gifford by chance.
</P>
<P>
   ''He began telling me about his ancestor who was in the
Revolutionary War and took part in the Boston Tea Party,'' Gifford
said. ''I couldn't believe it when he said the man was buried in
Stamford.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard told Gifford the grave didn't indicate that Theophilus
was a veteran. Gifford offered to submit the application to
properly mark Theophilus' grave.
</P>
<P>
   Within 30 days, a veteran's marker will be placed at Theophilus'
grave in Stamford, about 45 miles southwest of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 0148 </TRAILER>
