<HEADLINE> Gore Targets Prescription Drug Plan  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Courting Hispanics in a critical election-year
state, Vice President Al Gore said his plan to boost prescription
drug coverage under Medicare is needed most by Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ''Latinos are the most uninsured and underinsured population in
America,'' the likely Democratic presidential nominee said Monday,
adding that they have the most to gain from his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the number of Hispanics eligible for Medicare will
triple over the next 25 years and that nearly a third of those in
the program have poverty-level incomes. Hispanics also are more
than twice as likely to lack supplemental insurance coverage for
prescription medicines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will not come without a fight,'' Gore told thousands of
activists Monday at the annual convention of the National Council
of La Raza. ''I am committed to a real prescription drug benefit
for all Hispanics that rely on Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he sought to tie Republican presidential rival
George W. Bush to unpopular pharmaceutical companies that many
blame for high drug prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to take on the big drug companies,'' Gore said. ''I
know they are supporting the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal would provide a prescription drug benefit under
the Medicare program, with the government paying half of the annual
costs up to $5,000. Aides said it would extend coverage to 40
million people at a cost of $255 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett said Bush has been
consistent in proposing to allocate $5 trillion over five years to
both save and strengthen Social Security and Medicare, and also
provide prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore first headed Monday to St. Louis to meet with seniors and
tout his prescription drug plan, as well as to bash a proposal by
congressional Republicans that has Bush's support.
</P>
<P>
   That measure, which relies on insurance companies to provide
coverage instead of the government, is useless, said Gore. He
accused Republicans of allowing insurance interests to write the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they crafted the actual words,'' he said. ''It was
designed to make it appear they have a plan. They do not have a
plan. Its only purpose is to serve as an illusion or camouflage.
It's a fraud. Let's call it what it is, it is a fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore blamed soaring drug costs on ''price gouging'' by drug
makers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have fought this battle for more than two decades now,'' he
said. ''Governor Bush is supported by the companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign retorted that Gore has had eight years to devise
a prescription drug program but is doing so only as the
presidential campaign unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore met with seniors as he opened his latest swing
focused on the economy, he quickly headed to California to speak to
Hispanic activists. Later in the week, he was meeting with two big
teacher unions, though aides said he would continue to focus on the
prescription drug issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the number one issue for Hispanics, along with
education,'' said Gore campaign spokesman Chris Lehane. He added
that teachers who deal with children daily also are receptive to
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore left no stone unturned in courting members of the Hispanic
advocacy group on his 80th trip to California since becoming vice
president in 1993. California is the biggest prize in the
presidential contest, holding 54 of the 270 electoral votes needed
to win the election.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who also prowled the cavernous hall for an hour taking
questions on a range of issues, touted differences with Bush on
affirmative action and hate crimes laws.
</P>
<P>
   He also echoed a promise from Bill Clinton's 1992 presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''My Cabinet will look like America,'' Gore said. ''It will
embody the diversity of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's marathon campaign day, which began in Washington early
Monday, was ending there at dawn Tuesday after an all-night flight.
He was spending the Fourth of July away from the trail, marking the
first birthday of his grandson, Wyatt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
