<HEADLINE> Mason Incited Riot, Police Say  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Charlotte Hornets forward Anthony Mason was
arrested after he was accused of starting a riot and assaulting
police in the city's French Quarter on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, 33, of Charlotte, N.C., was arrested at about 10:15 p.m.
EDT after he was sprayed with pepper by officers, police spokesman
Joseph Narcisse said.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of officers noticed two groups of men arguing over women
on Bourbon Street, Narcisse said. When the officers tried to
separate the groups, Mason, who is 6-foot-8 and 270 pounds, hit one
of the officers and began rallying the crowd, Narcisse said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer who had been hit tried to subdue Mason with pepper
spray, but with little effect, Narcisse said.
</P>
<P>
   Other officers arrived and some in the crowd threw bottles and
shouted racial slurs at police, Narcisse said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason fled and the crowd followed him, while police went to the
8th District station, where they regrouped. They then arrested
Mason and took him to the city's charity hospital to have his face
treated, Narcisse said.
</P>
<P>
   No officers were seriously hurt in the melee, Narcisse said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason will be booked with inciting a riot, battery on police
officers and resisting arrest, Narcisse said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not Mason's first brush with the law. He was arrested on
two counts of misdemeanor assault last February after a scuffle
outside a barroom in New York. The charges were later dropped when
prosecutors said they did not have enough evidence to convict him.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who has played with New Jersey, Denver and the New York
Knicks, led the Hornets in 1997-98 in field goal shooting
percentage and rebounds for the second consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Mason has said in NBA promotions that he ''sees a
career in criminal justice after his playing career ends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 0211 </TRAILER>
