<HEADLINE> Supersonic flights not on the horizon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - An attempt to lure supersonic Concorde
jet service to upstate has failed.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 20 well-heeled travelers accepted a St. Louis company
offer of a two-week luxury trip from Rochester to Europe, costing
between $7,000 to $19,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't get as many bookings as hoped,'' said Jackie M.
Renda, marketing director for Montclair Travel of St. Louis. The
company's goal was to get at least 100 passengers for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Those who did sign up for the less than four-hour trip to Paris
and London will have to fly from New York City's JFK Airport and
meet the elegant Concorde at its usual stop there.
</P>
<P>
   A Concorde hasn't landed in Rochester since one of the
needle-nosed planes touched down at the Greater Rochester
International Airport carrying European Ryder Cup players and
Britain's Prince Andrew in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
