<HEADLINE> Next Up for Census: 'Best Guess'  </HEADLINE>
By GENARO C. ARMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Elnora Cooper is 76 years old, but she never
counted in the census until now.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first time I've ever filled it out,'' Cooper said
after Census Bureau workers urged her to do just that during an
event in the Philadelphia senior home she lives. ''I've been in
North Philadelphia for 50 years, but when I first saw that form, I
said 'what the devil is this?'''
</P>
<P>
   She's not the only one mystified. The agency estimates that in
the last census 10 years ago, it missed about 8 million people,
while double-counting 4 million for a net undercount of 1.6 percent
of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Census director Kenneth Prewitt is determined not to let that
happen again. But his statistical solution has generated more
problems -- and most of them don't have to do with mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   ''The census? It's to help people right? Yeah, why not fill it
out,'' said Ralph McCray, 28, as he waited for a friend in downtown
Baltimore. But did he fill his own form out? ''No, I forgot,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To account for people like Cooper and McCray, Prewitt wants to
use a statistical method known as ''sampling,'' based on a randomly
sampled follow-up survey of 314,000 households going on now. It is
separate from the head count the Census Bureau just completed of
120 million households across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we stopped the census today, we would have a good estimate
of the population of the United States based on the 120 million
households in our address file,'' Prewitt said after announcing the
agency finished its head count a week ahead of its July 7 targeted
completion date.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we do these operations to get these estimates closer to
the truth,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, sampling involves a complicated series of
mathematical formulas used to adjust the initial head count.
Sampling would help delete twice-counted persons, such as people
with two homes that mistakenly sent in forms from each address.
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat akin to balancing a checkbook. Often, errors are
found in the balance of a checkbook when compared to a bank
statement. You add and subtract dollars from the checkbook balance
to match up with the total on the bank statement.
</P>
<P>
   About half of those undercounted in 1990 were children.
Supporters say sampling would help account for them, as well as the
poor, minorities, and inner-city residents that tend to vote
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   And that has some Republicans worried. Since states now have the
option of using sampled data to reshape congressional and state
legislative district boundaries, some GOP leaders fear it could
create new districts with higher concentrations of Democratic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau plans to release both sets of numbers: the
actual head count by Dec. 31; and the sampled count, if approved,
by April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., chairman of the House Government Reform
Committee's census panel, has questioned whether the Census Bureau
sacrificed quality to speed up its head count, a charge Prewitt has
denied.
</P>
<P>
   Statistician David Murray, an appointee by the
Republican-controlled Congress to the Census Monitoring Board
oversight panel, says the bureau's sampling plan also has
statistical flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you engage in a sampling process, you are putting people
back in districts who may not be there, and you are also including
people who tend not to be engaged in the process,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   But while debate over sampling is likely to heat up in Congress
over the coming months, the issue may ultimately be decided in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia passed an anti-sampling law in April, but still needs
Justice Department approval since it falls under the Federal Voting
Rights Act of 1965 -- a law that Congress passed to ensure that no
discrimination occurs in connection with election law changes. Some
20 states, mostly in the South, are covered by the law.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia has asked a federal court to allow it to bypass
Justice, and other states are expected to follow Virginia's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a question that could ultimately be left up to the
courts. I think we all agree on that,'' Miller said at a recent
subcommittee hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Everitt Bryant, a Republican and Census director during
the Bush administration, supports sampling
</P>
<P>
   ''Redistricting is done at the state level, not by the Census
Bureau, and whichever party controls the state legislature and
governor's office usually has more influence on the way lines are
drawn, than any additional people a district has,'' said Bryant,
now a professor at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt says the Census Bureau's focus is on what is best
statistically, not politically. Though appointed by President
Clinton, Prewitt dismisses notions he has partisan intentions in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope (Americans) will understand that this additional work
is necessary to ensure that Census 2000 can provide the best
possible data to guide important decisions that will impact their
lives through the decade,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate goes on, the agency will continue with its
sampling survey, as well as conduct follow-up visits to 12 million
addresses to ensure the accuracy of answers they collected in the
head count.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people feel it's best not to answer the census, because
you don't know if it's going to hurt us or what,'' said Laverne
Johnson, who lives in the Robert Johnson Homes housing project in
Philadelphia. ''I just hope all this ain't for nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 1254 </TRAILER>
