<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda May Get Multiparty System  </HEADLINE>
By HENRY WASSWA
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- Five days after voters opted to stick
with his ''no-party'' system in a referendum marked by low turnout
and an opposition boycott, President Yoweri Museveni made the
surprise announcement that he was willing to consider a return to
multiparty politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no problem with political parties if they are not on
the wrong basis,'' he told a news conference. ''Let's change
society in such a way that if parties are brought in, they are no
longer a danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system -- and the one that voters approved --
the political parties are allowed to exist, but they can't field
candidates, canvas for funds or campaign under their colors.
</P>
<P>
   Western donor nations, who paid $4.5 million toward the cost of
the June 29 referendum, afterward expressed concern that the
outcome of the vote favoring Museveni's National Resistance
Movement would result in the establishment of a one-party system in
the East African nation.
</P>
<P>
   Voters, who were asked whether they wanted to retain the
Movement system or return to multiparty politics, opted for the
former with 91 percent of their votes. The turnout was 44.9 percent
of the 9.6 million registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Uganda People's Congress and the Democratic Party, the
historical opposition parties, boycotted the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Museveni said the Movement, to which every Ugandan theoretically
belongs under the 1995 constitution, would hold a convention to
discuss the future role of political parties in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Movement leaders will organize a convention and ask
ourselves whether we can change our stand toward parties. We shall
consult with people,'' he said. ''The Movement cannot be a
one-party system for the country because it is not a party, it is a
system of various ideologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Museveni has consistently blamed political parties for
exacerbating the ethnic and religious divisions that tore Uganda
apart in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Established before Uganda's independence from Britain in 1962,
the Democratic Party had strong Roman Catholic support and a large
following in Buganda, the home of Uganda's largest tribe, the
Baganda. The UPC was backed by Protestants and had wide following
in the north.
</P>
<P>
   After he took power in 1986 at the end of a five-year guerrilla
campaign, Museveni restricted party activities.
</P>
<P>
   ''By 1986 and following the sectarianism which has characterized
this country, we did not think that the time was ripe to tempt the
population with sectarianism, but that was 14 years ago,'' Museveni
said. ''Now, we have a new generation of people who are not
bothered by sectarianism.''
</P>
<P>
   Two opposition candidates ran against Museveni as private
individuals in the May 1996 presidential elections, which he won by
a landslide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 1345 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000704.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
