<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor to sign sprinkler bill, gives colleges more time to fix fire code violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman on Wednesday is
expected to sign legislation requiring New Jersey's public and
private colleges to install fire sprinklers in all dormitories
within four years.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is in response to a fire at Seton Hall
University Jan. 19 that killed three students and injured 62
others.
</P>
<P>
   Several colleges and universities, including Seton Hall, are
already moving ahead with installing sprinklers in every room in
time for the fall semester.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would appropriate $90 million to help pay for the
sprinklers. Public and private colleges and universities would get
interest-free loans, while boarding schools, military academies and
other schools that have dorms would have to repay the loans at 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill allows exemptions for certain buildings. That would
most likely apply to ''very small'' buildings, state officials have
said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimate that more than 36,000 college dorm beds
are located in rooms without sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the governor has given colleges and universities
another four months to bring buildings into compliance with fire
code regulations, The Star-Ledger of Newark reported in Tuesday's
editions.
</P>
<P>
   In granting the extra time, Whitman commended the progress
colleges have made so far to address code violations.
</P>
<P>
   The state began inspecting colleges and universities after the
Seton Hall fire. During an inspection in April, officials found
2,380 violations.
</P>
<P>
   The state Fire Safety Division said 236 violations remain in
need of correcting, and in almost all of those cases, the colleges
were granted extensions to complete the work.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has threatened to cut aid to those colleges and
universities that do not comply with her directive.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said the four-month extension gives the colleges the
summer to finish major projects while most students are gone. But
she has cautioned that minor or maintenance violations must not be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's comments came a day after a fire in a kitchen at Rowan
University in Glassboro caused about $10,000 in damage and forced
the evacuation of 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say the fire in the Student Center was unrelated
to safety inspections. However, Rowan University had ignored
frequent state citations for not installing a sprinkler system in
the basement of a gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   University officials say a $120,000 project to install
sprinklers likely will be completed this month. When it is
finished, all Rowan University buildings will have fire sprinklers,
university officials say.
</P>
<P>
   At Montclair State University, compliance has encountered some
delays. The school has contracts for repairs that include
installing fire doors, university spokeswoman Phyllis Miller told
The Star-Ledger.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's holding us up is it requires outside contractors and
requires public bidding,'' she told the newspaper. The work must be
done during the summer when residence halls are vacant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-04-00 1353 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000704.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protest Hits Ivory Coast Capital  </HEADLINE>
By GLENN McKENZIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- High-rise offices were empty and
streets abandoned in Ivory Coast's commercial capital Tuesday as
soldiers erected makeshift barricades and raced around in stolen
vehicles with rifles bristling.
</P>
<P>
   The protest by disgruntled army officers demanding perks closely
resembled a brief army mutiny that led to the nation's first coup
d'etat last December. And while officials and soldiers were
negotiating an end to the latest impasse, many civilians feared
another takeover in what has long been one of Africa's most stable
and prosperous nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are tired of these soldiers using guns to disrupt our
lives. We want democracy,'' said Nogbou Mensah, a taxi driver in
the Cocody suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The unrest began with a 30-minute burst of gunfire at 4 a.m.
that lasted for 30 minutes in several parts of Abidjan. Another
round of shooting occurred in the posh residential and commercial
district of Deux Plateau, around 9:30 a.m. and a smattering gunfire
was heard later.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy buildup of soldiers on foot and in armored personnel
carriers was visible around the airport, state broadcasters and
presidential mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the U.S. and Canadian embassies both said the
security situation was unclear and advised their citizens not to
venture into the streets. Some border posts were reportedly closed
and at least two airlines, Air France and British Airways, on
Tuesday suspended international flights from Abidjan.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers also blocked roads in several other Ivory Coast cities
and sporadic shooting was reported near a military base in the
northern town of Korhogo.
</P>
<P>
   The Ivory Coast is the world's largest cocoa producer and the
scare prompted cocoa prices on the London futures exchange to jump.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials and protesting soldiers were locked in
discussions to resolve the crisis, a senior defense ministry
official said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In a state television broadcast, Information Minister Henri
Cesar Sama said civilian safety was ''guaranteed'' but appealed to
the protesting soldiers to return to their barracks and negotiate
''in a disciplined and serene manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet after the announcement, protesting soldiers -- some drinking
beer and threatening civilians who ventured into the streets --
continued to cruise the streets in taxi, jeeps and other seized
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, mostly young army officers, have demanded lump
sums of $9,000 each to buy houses. Ivory Coast's cash-strapped
government cannot afford to meet the soldiers' demands, Sama said.
</P>
<P>
   Sama accused unnamed politicians of fomenting the unrest ''in
order to gain power by any means.'' Authorities were searching for
the instigators, he said. No arrests had been made.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to avoid bloodshed. It is still not over,'' Sama
said.
</P>
<P>
   At a military checkpoint outside the state television station, a
surly soldier driving a luxury car said: ''Tell the world this: The
government is stealing from the treasury and we have had enough. We
want our money.''
</P>
<P>
   The whereabouts of military leader Gen. Robert Guei was unclear.
Sama denied reports that Guei had fled his mansion, where there was
a heavy military presence, saying only that the junta leader was
''safe, unhurt and following the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The military protest came amid mounting political and ethnic
tensions in this West African country, which until the December
coup had long been one of the continent's most prosperous and
stable nations.
</P>
<P>
   Although the December coup was initially popular with Ivorians
who had grown tired of corruption and ethnic favoritism under
ousted President Henri Konan Bedie, many have since become
disillusioned with the new regime.
</P>
<P>
   Guei has promised elections for Sept. 17, but has not said
whether he will run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 1407 </TRAILER>
