<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tamil Tiger Position Destroyed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Sri Lankan troops attacked and
destroyed a Tamil Tiger rebel position in the northern Jaffna
peninsula on Tuesday, killing at least 23 militants, a government
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Government troops launched the operation in the Nagarkovil area,
21 miles northeast of Jaffna city, the Tamil rebels' former
stronghold from 1990-95 which the insurgents have been trying to
recapture.
</P>
<P>
   After the battle, soldiers recovered the bodies of 23
guerrillas, while two government soldiers were killed and 37
wounded in the fighting, said government spokesman Ariya
Rubasinghe.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, government troops attacked four Tamil Tiger bases
near Jaffna city, killing 12 guerrillas while three soldiers were
wounded, Rubasinghe said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, soldiers in the east repulsed a guerrilla attack on
their army camp. One soldier was killed in the assault.
</P>
<P>
   The army offensives follow a lull in recent fighting. The rebels
closed in on Jaffna city in a series of assaults in April and May,
but the military contained the push with newly acquired weapons,
Rubasinghe said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, the rebels have been fighting to carve out a
homeland in eastern and northern Sri Lanka for the country's
minority Tamils, who comprise 3.2 million of the country's 18.6
million people.
</P>
<P>
   More than 62,000 people have been killed in the 18 years of
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The government on Tuesday reinstated censorship on local media
and Colombo-based foreign journalists reporting on the country's
civil war, three days after the Supreme Court threw out the
measures on a technicality.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have reimposed some restrictions again as we felt that in
the interest of the nation there should be some restrictions on
news reporting,'' Rubasinghe told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pakistan assured Sri Lanka of continued support to
combat the guerrillas, the state-run Daily News said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has supplied the army with multibarrel rocket
launchers, which helped stop a Tamil assault on Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to support Sri Lanka,'' the newspaper quoted
Pakistani military ruler Gen. Pervez Musharraf as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
