<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria To Hold Referendum on EU  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE JAHN
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Austrians will get to voice their anger
over months of European Union sanctions in a nationwide referendum
that suggests the governing coalition could be seeking popular
support for threats to veto EU decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel said Tuesday that the decision to
hold the referendum was reached after six hours of deliberations by
a special committee of the government, including Joerg Haider and
members of his far-right Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   It was Haider's past praise of the Nazi era that contributed to
the EU 's decision to impose sanctions on Austria in February,
after Haider's party joined the coalition government. The Freedom
Party's harsh line on immigration and other issues affecting
foreigners also played a role in the EU's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, now a provincial governor, is not a member of the
federal government and has no formal say in government policy.
Still, he remains extremely influential and is thought to exercise
substantial control on Freedom Party members in the government.
</P>
<P>
   He has repeatedly warned that Austria will block EU legislation
normally requiring consensus unless the sanctions are lifted. In
particular, he has suggested that EU expansion eastward, to include
former Soviet bloc members, could be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel and other government ministers have refrained from
such overt threats, but the wording of two of the six referendum
questions indicated a desire to test public opinion on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian news agency said voters would be asked whether the
federal government should ''ensure with all possible means that the
unfairly imposed sanctions on Austria from the other members of the
European Union be lifted immediately?''
</P>
<P>
   Another question asks whether EU member nations should have the
right to choose their own governments without outside interference
-- a clear reference to the sanctions. The four other questions deal
with more general EU issues.
</P>
<P>
   An Austrian government statement Tuesday said the referendum
would not be held if the sanctions are lifted ahead of the date set
for the plebiscite. Possible dates for the referendum are Oct. 29
and Nov. 26, the news agency reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 1501 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
