<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jamaica Issues New TV Rules  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) -- Moving to bring Jamaica in line with
international intellectual property laws, the government has
ordered cable operators to stop illegal pickups of U.S.
pay-per-view channels and other satellite broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Those who ignore the order, effective Wednesday, face a fine of
$1,500 or three months imprisonment and could have their licenses
suspended, said Ian Miles, executive director of the government
Broadcasting Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Caribbean island's 37 cable TV operators are
broadcasting a pay-per-view movie channel and other stations picked
up from Direct TV satellite broadcasts in the United States without
permits, Miles said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not waiting for somebody to contact us before we take
the action,'' he explained. ''We know what the law requires in
terms of intellectual property compliance ... this is a global
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
