<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Counterdemonstrators outnumber supremacists at rally, 12 arrested  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORRISTOWN, N.J. (AP) - About a dozen counterdemonstrators were
arrested here Tuesday after knocking over or running past police
barricades separating them from a small group of white supremacists
staging a rally.
</P>
<P>
   Nine members or supporters of the Nationalist Movement staged
their rally and one-block march under heavy police guard on a side
street next to the Morris County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Leader Richard Barrett gave a 45-minute speech from the back of
a flag-decorated pickup truck, but he was hard to hear over the
racket made by those who came to Morristown to denounce him.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 counterdemonstrators staged their own protest
nearby on Washington Street, where scores of riot-geared sheriff's
deputies and other police kept guard between rows of barricades set
up to keep the groups apart.
</P>
<P>
   When the supremacists moved to Washington Street for a brief
march, some 30 sheriff's deputies with helmets and shields led the
way, and two dozen police officers followed, including eight
mounted police. When activities broke up hours later, teams of
officers were seen escorting individual supremacists safely to
their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Morris County Sheriff Edward Rochford said nearly 300 police
officers from 20 agencies, including a mounted patrol from as far
away as Camden County, came to town to help keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Brandishing the American flag and their own Nationalist flag,
bright red with a black cross, the supremacists called for an end
to affirmative action programs and protested the firing of New
Jersey State Police Superintendent Carl Williams last year at the
height of the controversy over racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   One banner read, ''America arise, destroy minority tyranny.''
Counterdemonstraters chanted, ''Death to fascists.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryle Lamont Jenkins, a member of the New Jersey Freedom
Organization, said, ''We're going to do the best we can to drown
them out.''
</P>
<P>
   The mini-rally was led by lawyer-activist Richard Barrett, who
argued in state and federal court for the group's rights to protest
on the steps of the historic courthouse. A federal judge moved
their event to the side street.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett has fought for marching rights across the nation and
before the U.S. Supreme Court. The Nationalist Movement, based in
Learned, Miss., claimed it would have 50 marchers here Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
