<HEADLINE> Cha-ching: Good weather, Tuesday holiday add up for shore merchants </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) - Good beach weather, a holiday and the
luck of the calendar added up to big business this weekend at the
shore, with vacationers and day-trippers taking advantage of a rare
four-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of heading home Sunday night or Monday morning, they
lingered on the beach and Boardwalk through midday Tuesday. Hazy,
hot weather and the promise of a nighttime fireworks display kept
parking lots full and merchants happy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't see how they could possibly pack any more people onto
these islands,'' said Brian Conger, owner of B.C. Sweet Jug, an ice
cream shop. ''I'm here 12 years, and this has been one of my best
holiday weekends ever. It was excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Day traditionally kicks off the summer season at the
shore, but iffy weather forecasts, cold ocean waters and school
commitments keep many visitors away until mid- to late June.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth of July weekend, always one of the season's busiest,
often serves as a barometer for the year. And store owners liked
what they saw this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good start to a slow season,'' said Nick Elmer, owner
of Surf Buggy Centers, which rents bicycles for $5 an hour and
surreys for $12. ''We've been a little slow this year, but it's
picking up now. Hopefully, it'll stay this way.''
</P>
<P>
   At Surf &AMP; Sand Beach Service, which rents chairs for $5 a day
and beach umbrellas for $8, business was brisk all weekend,
especially Sunday. The company's Moorlyn Terrace location rented
all 38 of its chairs and all 30 umbrellas by 1 p.m. Sunday, said
worker Pedro DeLeon.
</P>
<P>
   ''The weather was great. It was easily the busiest we've been
all season,'' DeLeon said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Ivory, who owns four Boardwalk stores that sell jewelry,
clothing and gifts, said business was excellent at each.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a huge weekend for us, and it didn't disappoint. Our
sales were high, our special orders were high, our customers were
happy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Tuesday was her busiest day, thanks to more good
weather and the nighttime fireworks display planned at Sixth
Street.
</P>
<P>
   On the Boardwalk, pedestrian traffic was as busy as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're here to stay now,'' said Karen Lightner, 29, of Ocean
City, who watched the sunburned beachgoers walk by from her spot on
a bench. ''They'll be here from now until September.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the passers-by were Larry and Lisa Schultz of
Wilkes-Barre, Pa., who brought their five children and two others
for the weekend. The children walked along the Schultzes, carrying
rubber rafts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't need to come here to drop a bundle of money; we
could have done that anywhere,'' she said. ''But it's really nice
here. That's why we come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
