<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB: Engine of banner-towing plane checks out  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LAKEWOOD, N.J. (AP) - The engine of a banner-towing plane that
crashed, killing the pilot, showed no irregularities when it was
inspected Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert T. Lewis, 44, of Omaha, Neb., died when the single-engine
propeller plane dove nose-first onto a Lakewood Airport runway
Monday. He was the only person aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The rope on an advertising banner that read ''Seton Hall, Go
Pirates'' became tangled in the plane's rudder, apparently causing
the crash. It was unclear whether Lewis was picking up the banner
or releasing it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought everything was fine. It had plenty of power and
everything,'' said Kute Anthony, of Wall, a pilot who was at the
airport at the time. ''But the plane stalled and rolled over and
just went down on its nose.''
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board spokesman Robert J. Gretz
said investigators found nothing unusual in their inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went through the whole engine today, didn't find any
discrepancies. The only discrepancy we found in the whole
investigation was the rope wrapped around the rudder of the
airplane,'' Gretz said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who was married with five children, had taken the
banner-towing job to help make ends meet. He started a crop-dusting
business in Nebraska two years ago, his wife, Catherine, told the
Asbury Park Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''Friday, Saturday, Sunday and (Monday) were the only days he
had flown,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis had planned to work here through July, but was considering
coming home early, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He missed us and was getting homesick,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
