<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> View from a bridge -- not to mention a park and port  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The Brooklyn Bridge offers one of New York's
most scenic views of Lower Manhattan. But only a few dozen people
took to its pedestrian walkway Tuesday midmorning to view the
flotilla of tall ships passing in front of the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a better view from up here,'' said Bob Friedman
as he stood on the bridge watching the stately vessels glide slowly
toward Manhattan's skyscrapers. ''It's so Gotham, with the haze
rising off the empty buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   At times fog all but obscured the ships' hulls, but their white
sails could be seen shimmering and billowing despite the haze.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   The Eagle has landed!
</P>
<P>
   Nobody actually said that Tuesday, but it was true: The Eagle -
a Coast Guard ship that led the OpSail flotilla - was the first
vessel to dock at historic South Street Seaport. Several hundred
people cheered as two small tugboats nudged the 295-foot-long
vessel flush with the old wooden pier without so much as a bump.
</P>
<P>
   Next to dock at the seaport was the Niagara, a two-masted,
square-rigged sailboat that was built in 1813, and then the
Danmark, a steel-hulled Danish ship that was welcomed by several
dozen Danes on the pier waving their country's flag - a white cross
on a red background.
</P>
<P>
   The Danmark, which was to dock right across from the Eagle in a
slip barely 75 feet wide, aborted one attempt to land, backed up,
sent sailors up the mast to tie up the billowing sails, and then
pulled smoothly in to the dock on its second try.
</P>
<P>
   The Danish Consulate's cultural attache, Irene Krarup, sighed
with relief and cheered as the ship came to a stop. ''They almost
couldn't fit through that little hole,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand people gathered at the Riverbank State Park in
Harlem to watch the ships travel up the Hudson. Adante Smith, 7,
whose tongue was pink from eating a cherry ice, knew exactly why
his mother had brought him there from Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm waiting for the pirate ships,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of thousands gathered at Battery Park across from the
Statue of Liberty. The spectators applauded as fighter planes
zoomed through the sky in formation, then oohed and aahed as the
first tall ships rounded Staten Island, looking otherworldly as
they approached through the mist.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were expecting a faster pace, but it was pretty neat to see
the old-style schooners,'' said Ryan Williams of Cranford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Senkier of Poughkeepsie wielded a camera and a pair of
binoculars for a close-up view, but noticed something funny as he
peered at the crews of the passing vessels.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people on the ships are taking as many pictures of us as
we're taking of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   No, that mysterious black UFO wasn't a lost kite or Batman come
to life. It was a Stealth bomber, part of the display of America's
military might that accompanied OpSail. But it swooped over the
city's waterways and skyscrapers so fast that many who saw it
simply shook their heads in wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ''What was that?'' asked a jogger on the Brooklyn Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   A woman walking by just shrugged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-04-00 1733 </TRAILER>
