<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands wait long hours for a glimpse of tall ships through the haze </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE ROTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - As towering tall ships with majestic white sails
paraded through New York Harbor on Independence Day, thousands of
people crowded along the banks of the Hudson River almost as far
north as the George Washington Bridge and waited for a glimpse. And
waited, and waited some more.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm looking as hard as I can but I can't see anything,''
complained George Nyers, a retiree, who sat on the edge of a park
bench craning his neck to see. He and thousands of others were in
place by 10 a.m. along the western edge of Riverbank State Park
around 142nd Street to see the ships.
</P>
<P>
   Children gave up looking as the morning went on, instead going
to massive barbecues in the park accompanied by Latino music.
Several formations of fighter planes flew overhead, but few
onlookers seemed impressed. There were no ships to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   It took a roaring Stealth bomber resembling a huge metal kite to
light up the rows of sweaty faces after 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yo! Yo! Yo!'' shouted a little boy, who jumped up and down and
pointed for his young friends to see.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Cearsy, 36, a fifth-grade teacher, looked up and said,
''Wow. I've only seen those in pictures before. All I know is
they're huge and that they cost a lot. ... But I still don't see
any ships.''
</P>
<P>
   People leaned over the railing, binoculars, cameras or video
cameras poised. But a U.S. Coast Guard cutter, some private white
motor boats and lots of mist were all that could be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Cearsy said she felt a raindrop fall as the clouds seemed to
grow darker. But no one seemed ready to give up waiting.
</P>
<P>
   At about 12:40 p.m., the first of the tall ships passed by the
crowded state park. Cannon fire resounded off the western banks of
Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yo ahoy matey!'' a half dozen boys in baggy shorts and long
T-shirts screamed.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rodriguez, a church supervisor from the Bronx, grinned
and shouted, ''Muy bonito! (Very pretty!)''
</P>
<P>
   Operation Sail marked the first return of the tall ships to New
York since 1992's 500th anniversary of Christopher Columbus's
journey. The 26 Class-A sailing ships, those over 160 feet, came
from 19 countries and had miles of canvas sails. More than 100
smaller wind-powered vessels also were part of the parade of sail.
</P>
<P>
   Waving a small American flag, 70-year-old Juana Pena's face
glowed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like the Nina, the Pinta, and the Santa Maria,'' she said
in Spanish, as she waved her flag more vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend Brenda Lee Childs, 50, who said she was a Cherokee
chief also known as Chief Nightlove Song Secorro, smiled as the
elegant ships sailed by.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been standing here since about 10:30 this morning but it
was worth the wait. ... It shows a part of our legacy - of when the
Spanish came,'' she said, trying to feel what the sight must have
been like for native Americans who saw ships for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can imagine when my ancestors were here and saw the ships
arrive. But I like it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome McArthur, standing nearby, put his feelings in one
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good day to be alive,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-04-00 1744 </TRAILER>
