<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Master of Sailing, Geometry Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMARONECK, N.Y. (AP) -- C. Stanley Ogilvy, a mathematics
professor at Hamilton College who wrote as expertly about geometry
as sailing, died at his home on June 21. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy taught for 20 years at Hamilton and wrote books and
articles on mathematics, while dozens of articles were written
about his expertise in sailing.
</P>
<P>
   Known to the nautical community as the ''Wise Professor,'' he
raced the class of boat known as the Star, a 23-foot-long, two-man
boat, for more than 30 years, placing third in the world
championships in 1949. Among his numerous victories were the North
American championship and the Austrian national championship.
</P>
<P>
   He then progressed to a larger class of boats, the Etchells,
which use a three-member crew, and had more success, particularly
at competitions of the Larchmont Yacht Club, where he was a member
for 62 years and the official historian.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy attended Williams College, Cambridge University and
Columbia University, eventually earning his doctorate in
mathematics from Syracuse University. In World War II, he commanded
a Navy air sea rescue vehicle in the South Pacific. He taught at
Trinity College before joining Hamilton's faculty in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy's books on sailing included three on one-design racing,
the term for classes of boats, like Stars, in which all boats meet
identical specifications. These were ''Successful Yacht Racing,''
''Thoughts on Small Boat Racing'' and ''Win More Sailboat Races.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy never married. He is survived by a brother, Stephen, of
Westport, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 1745 </TRAILER>
