<HEADLINE> Steinhauer Leads U.S. in Golf  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOUFFVILLE, Ontario (AP) -- Sherri Steinhauer's par at the final
hole enabled the United States to successfully defend the Nations'
Cup women's golf title Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Coe-Jones, who led by one going to the final hole, could
have earned Canada the victory but missed a par putt. While that
meant Canada and the United States both finished the tournament
with 4&AMP;frac12; points, the Americans won because they were defending
champions.
</P>
<P>
   With the other four singles matches complete and the teams tied
4-4, it came down to Coe-Jones' against Steinhauer over the par-72,
6,400-yard Emerald Hills Golf Club course.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't pretty but that's golf,'' said Steinhauer, a
five-time winner on the LPGA Tour. ''You just have to play with
what you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Coe-Jones, who trailed Steinhauer by three holes through nine,
went ahead for the first time at the par-4, 404-yard 14th. The
Canadian, a 17-year LPGA veteran, made a par and took the lead when
Steinhauer, a 15-year pro, settled for a bogey after putting her
drive behind trees in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   After missing a 6-foot birdie putt at No. 15 that would have
given her a two-hole advantage, Coe-Jones surrendered the lead with
a bogey at No. 16 where she put her drive into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Coe-Jones went up by one at No. 17 when Steinhauer bogeyed the
par-5, 440-yard hole after placing her third shot over the green
and into the deep rough.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any athlete in any game, be it an overtime goal in hockey or a
winning putt on the last hole, that's what you play for,''
Coe-Jones said. ''I was there and didn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't putt well, I didn't hit the ball well and neither did
Sherri. We were just hanging in there. We both made mistakes at
costly times, unfortunately for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada appeared in control heading into the singles competition,
leading 3-1 after splitting the alternate shot matches earlier
Tuesday. All the Canadians had to do was win two of the five
singles matches to avenge last year's 8-1 loss to the United States
in the inaugural tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Americans who dominated singles, winning three of
the four opening matches. Brandi Burton defeated Lorie Kane 3 and
2, Wendy Ward beat Nancy Harvey 4 and 3 and Nancy Scranton downed
Gail Graham 5 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Eathorne claimed the only Canadian victory, defeating
Michelle McGann 4 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauer and Ward earned the Americans their first point,
beating Graham and Coe-Jones 3 and 2 in the alternate-shot event
earlier. Kane and Eathorne won the other match, beating Burton and
McGann 1-up.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian captain Sandra Post took no solace in the close finish.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our team believed we were going to win,'' she said. ''And to
say that we did better this year isn't any consolation. We tasted
victory. It was right there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
