<HEADLINE> Lazio marches in three parades to mark July Fourth  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TICONDEROGA, N.Y. (AP) - Republican Senate candidate Rick Lazio
marched in three Fourth of July parades in northern New York on
Tuesday while trumpeting his accomplishments for veterans in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to pointing at his own record, Lazio's campaign
pressed its criticism of Democratic opponent Hillary Rodham
Clinton, who was with President Clinton in New York City observing
OpSail 2000, the parade of tall ships on the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's out taking an aircraft carrier for a vanity cruise and
we're out here on Main Street,'' said Lazio political strategist
Mike Murphy. ''I think it really tells the story of the difference
in the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast for Korean War veterans in Saratoga Springs
earlier Tuesday, Lazio himself questioned the first lady's
commitment to veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it goes back to, you know, 'What have you done for New
York?''' Lazio said. ''When New York needed Mrs. Clinton to fight
for veterans health benefits, where was she?''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also publicized his support for a number of
veterans-related initiatives in Congress and also claimed he has
fought Clinton administration efforts to divert funding for
veterans benefits from New York to ''southern states like Arkansas
and Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said:
''Rick Lazio's rhetoric doesn't match his record. While Hillary
Clinton worked to make treating Gulf War illness a government
priority, Rick Lazio was voting (in 1995) to cut $1 billion from
the Administration's veterans budget.''
</P>
