<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Successor to embattled mayor who resigned will continue polices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) - In his first public statement since embattled
and turbulent Mayor Edward A. Hanna resigned unexpectedly, interim
mayor Timothy J. Julian said he will continue the policies of his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna, a Utica political fixture with a knack for drawing
attention nationally for his unconventional, combative style,
resigned unexpectedly effective Tuesday morning. The 78-year-old
Republican said health concerns prompted him to resign. He also
faces sexual harassment allegations made in June by four men who
allege their employment was tied to their responses to the mayor's
advances.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Hanna denied the allegations, calling them part of
a ''cleverly orchestrated conspiracy to extort money, including
political rewards and control.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's lawyer, Joseph Policelli, countered by telling the
Utica Observer-Dispatch: ''People don't blackmail people by
claiming that they had homosexual activities with somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna's legacy is peppered with outrageous incidents. He once
proposed closing city government and he also built a Tower of Hope
next to City Hall to honor Bob Hope. Hope has no connection to
Utica.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna was also a stern fiscal watchdog. When the city's bonds
received the poorest rating of any city in the country in 1996, the
mayor opined, ''We got just what we deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna said he will help Julian, 35, who was common council
president, in the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ran with the mayor last year believing in his principles and
his theories. I still believe in them and still believe they will
move the city forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna was a self-made millionaire who said he brought ''sound
business practices'' to city government in two two-term stints as
mayor, the first time in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Julian's decision to begin his term as interim mayor with a
hastily arranged news conference was itself a departure from the
style of Hanna, who typically communicated with the media by press
release.
</P>
<P>
   After his prepared statement, Julian answered questions from
reporters for another 20 minutes, until his brother, Robert Julian,
the Republican leader of the Oneida County Board of Legislators,
brought the question and answer session to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Julian said he learned only at 9 p.m. Monday that Hanna had
decided to resign, according to the Utica Observer-Dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe (he) has been the best mayor this city has ever
had,'' he said. ''I regret his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Julian did not refer to the allegations of sexual misconduct
against Hanna that preceded his resignation, but he stressed that
the business of government would continue without pause despite the
tumult of recent weeks that Hanna referred to as a pressure cooker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-04-00 1845 </TRAILER>
