<HEADLINE> Four-year-old girl in wreck improving  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) - A 4-year-old girl's condition improved
Tuesday after she was injured in a weekend head-on collision in
Warren County that killed four people and sent seven others to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Johnelle Ponton of Newark, Del. was in fair condition at UNC
Hospitals in Chapel Hill, a hospital official said. She had been in
critical condition on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's accident occurred when the driver of a Mercury Grand
Marquis hit a guardrail and lost control of the car about 7 miles
south of the North Carolina-Virginia border, the Highway Patrol
said. The car then crossed the median and into the path of a Toyota
Camry.
</P>
<P>
   All of the dead were in the Toyota. The driver, Lailaa Fofana,
53, of Philadelphia, was killed as were passengers Rodney Chavis,
57, of Harrisburg, Pa.; Mary Chavis, 74, of Willlingboro, N.J.; and
Tonia Austin, 15, of Newark, Del. Johnelle and another woman in the
Toyota survived the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The five people in the Mercury were injured - one remained in
the hospital in satisfactory condition. The driver, Estelle
Douglas, 57, of Austell, Ga., was treated for injuries and
released.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol is not sure why Douglas lost control of the
car. No charges have been filed.
</P>
</TEXT>
