<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Imposes Curfew in Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUDERMES, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops in Chechnya threatened to
fire without warning on violators of a new curfew Tuesday as they
rounded up more than 58 suspects in connection with a series of
suicide truck-bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The troops searched several Chechen towns and cities for
suspected rebels Tuesday. Police detained 46 people in the
southwestern town of Urus-Martan, the site of one of Sunday's five
blasts, and a dozen other rebels were captured elsewhere, military
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Valery Manilov, first deputy chief of the Russian
general staff, said Tuesday that the official military toll from
the bombings was 33 soldiers killed, 84 wounded, and six missing.
</P>
<P>
   At least 11 civilians were killed, according to the Emergency
Situations Ministry. At least six rebels died when the trucks blew
up.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Federal Security Service, the main successor to
the KGB, on Tuesday blamed lax military commanders for failing to
prevent the bombings despite intelligence warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The blasts ''are the failures of the commanders who are in
charge there,'' Nikolai Patrushev was quoted by the Interfax news
agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors of one the worst bombings recalled the attack on their
barracks in the village of Argun.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was watching television with the guys. It's the last thing I
remember. I regained consciousness when the guys were digging me
out of the ground,'' Lt. Vladimir Volodin told The Associated Press
on Tuesday. He suffered a broken leg and a chest injury, and was
scarred by shrapnel wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Volodin was recovering in a hospital in the city of Vladikavkaz,
just west of the Chechen border.
</P>
<P>
   That blast, which killed 26 soldiers, was one of the attacks on
Russian forces in Chechnya that night -- the Russians' biggest
setback in months. The attacks underscored the difficulty Russia is
having in defeating the rebels, despite far more troops and fire
power.
</P>
<P>
   Volodin said fighting was raging as he regained consciousness
and it took two hours before he was extracted from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Another soldier injured in Argun said that despite shrapnel
wounds and a broken pelvis, he managed to return rebel fire after
the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ''After the explosion, I managed to get out of the debris on my
own,'' said Lt. Sergei Yefremenko. ''Fighting was in progress. I
rushed to my platoon's location, unaware of the pain, snatched a
machine gun and began firing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yefremenko said rebels opened fire with grenade launchers after
the blast. He said he passed out from the pain after he started
shooting and didn't see the end of the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces have now threatened to fire without warning on
any vehicle that violates a new curfew in Chechnya. Security was
also tightened in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Russian aircraft and artillery on Tuesday bombarded the Argun
and Vedeno gorges, which are key rebel refuges, and the southern
regions of Itum-Kale and Shali.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war.
They returned in September, after Islamic militants raided several
villages in the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan, and after
about 300 people died in a series of apartment bombings the
government blames on Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   One of the alleged leaders of the Dagestan invasions, Magomed
Tagayev, was arrested in Turkey last week, Dagestan police said
Tuesday. They said Russia will ask Turkey to extradite him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 1919 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000704.0106 </DOCNO>
