<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal cash to come to Delaware beaches for rebuilding  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER THORNE
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEWEY BEACH, Del. (AP) - To Robert Fredericks, the shorts and
sunglass-wearing mayor of this resort town, the sand under his feet
is no ordinary mineral.
</P>
<P>
   ''This sand is something we treat like gold,'' he said. ''We
groom it, we maintain it.''
</P>
<P>
   But all the attention may not be healthy. Some of Delaware's
beaches, visited by thousands from Maryland, Pennsylvania and
Washington, D.C. each weekend, are steadily being swallowed up by
the ocean. And the solution - the largest beach-rebuilding project
in state history - is on hold, awaiting action on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House of Representatives has budgeted more than $3.5
million to rebuilding Delaware's beaches - half of what state
leaders say is needed to complete the Rehoboth Beach-to-Fenwick
Island project. If approved by the Senate, the budget must pass the
Clinton administration, a longtime foe of beach restoration
projects.
</P>
<P>
   If no federal dollars are budgeted for Delaware's beaches, the
state will do what it can with $3.4 million of its own money, said
Robert Henry, administrator of the Shoreline and Waterway
Management Section of the state Department of Natural Resources and
Environmental Control.
</P>
<P>
   Given the delays, tourists won't have more sand to lay their
towels on until the summer of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The beaches can't wait forever. A report released last week
found Sussex County has one of the highest rates of coastal erosion
in the country. The Federal Emergency Management Agency estimated
that rising sea levels will eat away at an average of 3-4 feet of
beach every year for the next 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting beach loss, however, is an inexact science, said
Wendy Carey, a coastal processes specialist with the University of
Delaware Marine Advisory Serve and Sea Grant College Program.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been going to Rehoboth for 30 years now, and maybe the
beach is a little more narrow now, but not down at the south end of
the boardwalk,'' Carey said. ''It's the same as it was in 1964.''
</P>
<P>
   The science of restoring beaches is also subject to debate. Some
advocate for what is known as a ''retreat'' policy: Abandon the
beaches to nature's ebbs and flows, and allow homes and buildings
to fall in the ensuing erosion.
</P>
<P>
   Fredericks opposes letting nature take its course. Besides the
private houses that would be lost, there are millions of dollars
worth of coastal roads, sewers and other infrastructure that would
be swept away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't any sand deposited on the beach in a restructuring
project just eventually be lost again?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily, Carey said. People tend to think of the beach
as only the area where they can lay their towels, she said.
Scientists, however, know the beach includes a wide, flat span in
front of the ''towel beach'' that lies under just a few feet of
water. Most of the sand that appears to wash away is simply moved
onto that flat span. When the currents change, the sand is
redeposited on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't disappear,'' Carey said. ''The sand stays in the
system, adjusting to the waves and the profile of the current.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding a beach is a massive public works project, with
bulldozers and graders smoothing out wet sand pumped up from the
ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Corps has yet to find a sand bar appropriate for the
Delaware beach project, Henry said. The Corps scrapped its first
choice of an offshore shoal after concerns of damage to shellfish
habitat were raised.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes odd problems crop up in a beach replenishing project.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the state pumped 1.3 million cubic yards of sand from
the ocean floor onto the beaches of Bethany Beach and Fenwick
Island.
</P>
<P>
   First, the grain of the sand turned out to be too small, making
the dunes more vulnerable to erosion. Then, treasure seekers found
unexploded 40 mm shells - believed to have been fired into the
ocean decades before by National Guard tanks.
</P>
<P>
   But that's no reason to give up beach restoration, supporters
say.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in pretty good shape now, barring a hurricane or a
nor'easter,'' Fredericks said. ''But we need this to happen. It
absolutely would be a death sentence if it didn't. Our beach would
surely, slowly go away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
