<HEADLINE> Holiday weekend marked by police crackdown, drownings  </HEADLINE>
	   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least two motorists lost their lives in motor vehicle
accidents in Connecticut over the Fourth of July weekend, while
state police issued hundreds of tickets for speeding and not
wearing seatbelts.
</P>
<P>
   In Sharon, a 79-year-old man was killed Saturday when his pickup
truck veered off Route 7 and down an embankment into the Housatonic
River, state police said. Warren Buck, of Falls Village, was
pronounced dead at Hartford Hospital, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   An East Hartford man died after his motorcycle was involved in
an accident with another car in Rocky Hill. Police said William
Whinnem, 42, was pronounced dead at Hartford Hospital after the
accident Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On Interstate 91 at exit 8, a car plunged off of an overpass
bridge into the Quinnipiac River Tuesday, but the driver was not
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   State police were searching for a gunman in a car who fired on
another car early Tuesday on Interstate 91 in the North Haven area.
No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Some of most serious incidents occurred in water.
</P>
<P>
   In Mansfield, a 14-year-old girl died Sunday after losing
consciousness while swimming in a pool at a condominium complex.
Becky Baxter was in the pool just before 2 p.m. Sunday when she
lost consciousness, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   At Lake Compounce amusement park in Bristol, a 5-year-old
Hartford boy nearly drowned on a water ride. Devon M. Alexander,
who was underwater for about 25 minutes before lifeguards found
him, was in critical condition Tuesday at Connecticut Children's
Medical Center, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Four police officers were hospitalized Tuesday trying to break
up a scuffle at Ocean Beak State Park in New London. Police said
the scuffle started as a family dispute, and escalated into a brawl
around 3 p.m. Police used pepper spray to control the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Four people were arrested. Two bystanders - including a
12-year-old child - also were entangled in the scuffle. None of the
injuries appear to be serious.
</P>
<P>
   As of noon Monday, state police said they had issued 551 tickets
for not wearing a seatbelt, and 1,380 tickets for speeding.
Authorities also made 67 arrests charging motorists with driving
under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   More arrests and tickets were issued Tuesday, but specific
figures would not be released until Wednesday, said Sgt. Paul
Vance, state police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''The numbers definitely are going to go up,'' Vance said.
</P>
<P>
   State police reported no major traffic tieups Tuesday evening,
but traffic was expected to build into the night as vacationers
returned home from the long holiday weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
