<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan has Liberty, Freedom and Independence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LIBERTY, Mich. (AP) - Michigan is a state with Liberty, Freedom
and Independence - according to the map anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Like most states, Michigan has its share of patriotically named
cities, townships and lakes that might be perfect places to
commemorate the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the original settlers were drawing a town on the map, it
was usually an individual or a few individuals who were naming
it,'' said Sandra Clark, director of the Michigan Historical
Center. ''They'd name cities according to what their whims might
be, and they often were trying to make a political statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberty, a town in southern Jackson County, came from
Revolutionary War activist Patrick Henry's famous speech: ''Give me
liberty or give me death,'' according to the book ''Michigan Place
Names.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the town founder's apparent zeal for American
patriotism, don't look for an exciting Independence Day celebration
in Liberty. The closest festivities are in Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   Early settlers weren't always as showy with their patriotism as
the founders of Liberty, where the township hall proudly proclaims
''freedom rings.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Lansing for example. A group of settlers from New York
named the city after Lansing, N.Y., which itself was named after a
Revolutionary War hero.
</P>
<P>
   ''What you've usually got is a small group of farm families
getting together and deciding they're a town,'' Clark told The
Jackson Citizen Patriot for a story published Tuesday. ''If they're
going to form a town, they need a name, and they often choose the
place they moved from.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true of Independence Township in Oakland County. It was
named after Independence, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   For some in the Detroit area, patriotic names came from local
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Hamtramck received its moniker from the American
colonel who oversaw the transfer of Detroit in 1796 from Britain to
the United States, according to Michigan Place Names.
</P>
<P>
   Some Detroit residents in 1825 named Ypsilanti after Demetrius
Ypsilanti, a hero in the Greek war of independence in the early
1820s.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for every unusual name, Clark says, there are dozens of
obvious examples of early patriotism in action. The names of the
United States' first presidents show up frequently.
</P>
<P>
   And some Michigan counties - Van Buren, Calhoun and Eaton - were
named in the early 1830s after members of President Andrew
Jackson's cabinet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-04-00 2008 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000704.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One man's patriotic mission: 9- by 12-foot Declaration of Independence </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) - The Declaration of Independence
painstakingly copied to a cloth 9 feet by 12 feet is hanging again
near the turning point of the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   James Mathias' tribute on white drop cloth complete with the
founding fathers' signatures waved for 40 July Fourths at his
Saratoga Springs home 25 miles north of Albany. The former history
professor at Yale University spent a full winter on the work he
displayed proudly since the late 1950s. But when he died seven
years ago, the tradition died, too.
</P>
<P>
   This year his wife, Barbara, 87, who also has a doctorate in
history with a concentration in British history, revived the
tradition elsewhere in the city.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the black script on white background waved from the
Woodlawn Commons senior citizen apartments. Barbara Mathias says
she's thrilled she could renew the tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Springs is 4 miles north of the site of the Battle of
Saratoga, a turning point for the Colonies in the American
Revolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-04-00 2010 </TRAILER>
