<DOCNO> APW20000704.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Rescued in South Africa  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DASSEN ISLAND, South Africa (AP) -- Lying on his stomach, Tony
Williams reached into a burrow, grabbed a terrified penguin chick
by the neck and put it in a ventilated cardboard box.
</P>
<P>
   The chick rescued Tuesday was one of more than 10,000 birds
relocated since Sunday from Dassen Island off South Africa's west
coast to save them from swimming through an oil tanker's spill.
</P>
<P>
   Dassen Island has the world's largest colony of penguins, and
the three-day operation is the largest evacuation of wild birds
ever undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster began when a Panamanian tanker, the Treasure, sank
six miles off Cape Town on June 23 with 1,300 tons of oil.
</P>
<P>
   The slick quickly hit Robben Island, which has the world's third
largest number of African penguins, and last Wednesday reached
Dassen Island.
</P>
<P>
   Marine biologist Dr. Tosh Moller said at least 500 tons of oil
had escaped from the Treasure, 100 tons more than other estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The animal welfare fund said about 44 percent of the African
Penguin population, estimated at between 150,000 and 180,000 birds
had been affected by the spill.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the Dassen Island's bays, where up to 4,000 penguins
usually nest, just a few hundred remain.
</P>
<P>
   Williams estimated between 5,000 and 10,000 birds on Dassen
island had become contaminated with oil.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to remove oiled birds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Captured birds were flown off the island by helicopter Tuesday,
then trucked eight hours up the coast, where they will be released
into the ocean to swim home -- a journey expected to take about 11
days.
</P>
<P>
   However, with cleanup operations hampered by unfavorable
weather, there are growing fears the oil slick will still be there
when the penguins return home.
</P>
<P>
   The International Fund for Animal Welfare, said its survey
flight Monday showed the slick now covered about 20 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-mile-long stretch of coast -- which includes some of the
city's most popular beaches -- has also been coated in oil. Cleanup
operations are under way.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of oil-coated birds are being treated at
rehabilitation centers in Cape Town -- the bulk of them collected
from Robben Island, four miles off Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   International wildlife experts from the United States, Britain,
Europe and Canada have flown in to help deal with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Scarth, South Africa director of the fund, said Tuesday
the rehabilitation process was beginning to run smoothly and they
soon would be washing between 500 and 1,000 birds a day.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists turned their attention Tuesday to the older
chicks who will be ready to fend for themselves within a few weeks.
In the interim, they are to be hand-reared on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are far fewer birds on the island than we thought --
clearly many are still at sea,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The island's birds were fenced in Friday to prevent them from
entering the polluted water to fish. The fences were removed
Tuesday to enable those birds who had not been captured to resume
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists hope they will not encounter the oil slick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 2032 </TRAILER>
