<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports Drug Agency To Investigate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The Australian Sports Drug Agency will
investigate claims by a former Olympic discus thrower that
high-ranking Australian Olympic officials had secretly encouraged
widespread drug use among athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Werner Reiterer, a finalist at the 1992 Olympics, said doping
tests had been timed so he would escape detection for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Australians swimmers and track athletes were still using the
banned performance-enhancing substance, human growth hormone, he
was quoted saying in Wednesday's Sydney Morning Herald newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Human growth hormone is undetectable using conventional doping
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Reiterer, the 1994 Commonwealth Games gold medalist, retired
before the 1996 Olympics but made a comeback in 1997 before
quitting again earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was subtly encouraged to take drugs following his
return, adding that he was given advice from ''an Olympic
administrator'' about pending doping tests and about what levels of
certain substances were acceptable in the testing.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations were contained in his book ''Positive,'' which
was set to be launched Wednesday in Sydney. He said he didn't mind
being the whistle blower because he wanted Australians to see his
case was just the tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   Reiterer said he ''witnessed the complicity, mass delusion and
shadowy hypocrisy of sport's public face.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was another guilty athlete swallowed up in a sporting
culture largely organized around the use of illicit drugs,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Sports Drug Agency chief executive Natalie Howson
said there was no evidence to support Reiterer's allegations, ''but
I'll be looking into them very thoroughly and treating them very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Our systems are set up against international standards that
are designed to minimize athletes avoiding testing,'' Howson told
the Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio.
</P>
<P>
   ASDA had been empowered to conduct increased doping tests of
Australian athletes this year.
</P>
<P>
   As the testing agency for Sydney 2000 Olympics organizers, ASDA
will be conducting random and out-of-competition tests on athletes
of all nationalities leading to the Sept. 15-Oct. 1 Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
