<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Connecticut inmate dies of heart failure at Wallens Ridge  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A 50-year-old Connecticut inmate at a
maximum-security Virginia prison has died of apparent heart
failure, correction officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence James Frazier, formerly of Bridgeport, died at 1:14
a.m. Tuesday at Wallens Ridge State Prison in Big Stone Gap, Va. ,
said John Armstrong, the state's corrections commissioner. Frazier,
who was serving a 30-60 year sentence for multiple counts of sexual
assault, was pronounced dead at Lonesome Pines Hospital, Armstrong
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier's conviction stems from an incident in 1974 in which he
was convicted of repeatedly raping a woman during a robbery in her
home in Westport, said corrections spokesman Scott Semple.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier had been taken to the prison's medical unit on June 29
for a health problem, but was stabilized, the commissioner said.
After Frazier was cleared by a doctor, Armstrong said, the inmate
became a behavioral problem.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier was then restrained in a medical cell, Armstrong said,
where he was later found unresponsive. Staff members tried to
revive him, and Frazier was taken to the hospital on June 29 and
remained on life support until he died Tuesday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said preliminary reports show that Frazier suffered
heart failure. An autopsy will be conducted to determine the cause
of death.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Connecticut and Virginia will investigate the
death.
</P>
<P>
   Wallens Ridge has come under fire in recent months. In April,
David Tracy, a 20-year-old inmate from Bridgeport, hanged himself
in his cell at Wallens Ridge. A month earlier, three Connecticut
inmates were shot with rubber bullets by guards trying to break up
a scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Alvin Penn, D-Bridgeport, said inadequate medical
attention was a concern he heard voiced by inmates and their family
members during his recent to the Virginia prison. Penn said he
heard complaints about both the prison's routine medical and
emergency response procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a situation that is occurring at Wallens Ridge,'' he
said. ''There is a pattern that seems to be forming. There needs to
be answers.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of Connecticut's contract with Virginia, Wallens Ridge
will not accept inmates with serious medical conditions, said state
Rep. Michael Lawlor, D-East Haven. As a result, Lawlor said, the
prison provides ''the bare minimum'' in terms of medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   If Frazier had a known medical condition, Lawlor questioned why
the man was sent to Wallens Ridge in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very risky thing to have 500 inmates down there,''
Lawlor said, adding that should there be a lawsuit in connection
with the prison contract, Connecticut would be held responsible.
</P>
<P>
   But Semple said Tuesday that Frazier met all of the health
criteria to make him eligible for Wallens Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   The state Commission on Human Rights and Opportunities has
launched an investigation into allegations that the overwhelmingly
white prison staff has hurled racial insults at Connecticut
inmates, beat them and denied access to lawyers and religious
services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
