<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Military Defuses Troop Protest  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL ALEXANDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The military quelled a protest by troops at a
Fiji army base Wednesday, but said local chiefs threatened
disturbances in support of rebels who have been holding 27 people
hostage for seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three soldiers who were sympathetic to rebel leader
George Speight had confiscated arms and ammunition Tuesday inside
the base at Labasa, on the northern island of Vanua Levu.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of the arms are back in the armory and the soldiers have
resumed normal duty,'' Lt. Col. Filipo Tarakinikini told The
Associated Press. ''But some of the chiefs in the area who
apparently were behind this move are still holding on.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the chiefs had not undertaken any specific actions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's more the threat that they represent,'' Tarakinikini said.
''They can cause disturbances. Police have gone around and warned
shops that they might have to be closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Speight had predicted Tuesday the mutiny would spark a ''domino
effect'' across the country, but there were no signs of other
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Schools were closed on Fiji's main two islands, a day after five
rebels were wounded in a shootout with troops outside the
Parliament compound.
</P>
<P>
   The situation at Parliament was reported to be tense but calm.
Tarakinikini said efforts were under way to arrange ''preliminary''
talks aimed at ending the hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The new government, installed Tuesday by the military over
Speight's objections, was settling in to face a massive task: how
to stem the economic decline sparked by the May 19 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Most top tourist resorts have been hit hard, with some reporting
occupancy rates of only 10 percent, and rebuilding confidence among
foreigners will be a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   New Prime Minister Laisenia Qarase, a former banking executive,
has said ending the hostage crisis will remain the military's
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how a 15-minute firefight on Tuesday -- which each
side accused the other of starting -- would affect those efforts. No
negotiations have been held since a near-agreement broke down at
the last minute last week.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the military on Monday to appoint a new
government comprised entirely of indigenous Fijians would appear to
meet Speight's stated goals.
</P>
<P>
   When he and his men stormed Parliament on May 19, he said he
only was trying to safeguard native rights.
</P>
<P>
   Qarase said the 1997 Constitution would be replaced to strike a
balance between ensuring the rights of indigenous Fijians come
first and serving as a ''framework for living together as a
multiracial and multicultural society.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Speight was angry at the military's
unilateral appointments because they did not include his choice to
head the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''The actions of the army are ... considered insulting,
provocative and devoid of any consideration of the stability of the
country,'' the former insurance executive said, adding that he did
not expect the new government to be in power long.
</P>
<P>
   Commodore Frank Bainimarama, who assumed power 10 days after the
coup, appointed the interim leaders. He has said he will retain
power until the captives are freed.
</P>
<P>
   The army has given in to most of Speight's demands to
disenfranchise Fiji's ethnic Indians, including firing Prime
Minister Mahendra Chaudhry -- the first Fijian of Indian ancestry to
lead the country. Chaudhry is among the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Indians were brought to Fiji over a century ago by English
colonialists seeking indentured laborers for rich sugar cane
fields. They make up about 44 percent of Fiji's population;
indigenous Fijians account for about 51 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
