<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Oil Firm Caught in Dispute  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN McNAMARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANOUAN, St. Vincent (AP) -- An increasingly strident border
dispute could cost both Guyana and Suriname a fortune in oil
revenues and kill the Caribbean's most promising exploration,
officials of a Canadian oil company said at a regional summit
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   CGX Energy Inc.'s rig was ready to start drilling a month ago
when Surinamese military moved in on boats and ordered it away,
since the site is in disputed waters at the mouth of the Corentyne
River on South America's northeast coast. Suriname says the border
extends from the river at a 10-degree angle; Guyana says it's a
24-degree angle.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday -- the second day of talks at a summit of the
14-nation Caribbean Community -- Surinamese government spokesman
Borger Breeveld said his country was not open to a Guyanese
proposal to share the profits from the oil but leave the border
where it is.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sharing the oil would set a precedent. Next time Guyana will
come up with the same thing,'' Breeveld said. ''Suriname wants to
settle the border issue once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Sully, president of the Toronto company, said the company
could decide this week to postpone exploration under its 10-year
concession in Guyana for several years until the issue is settled.
</P>
<P>
   He said the exploration could benefit Suriname as well because
the disputed area is key to unlocking the entire Suriname-Guyana
basin -- which the U.S. Geological Survey estimates holds 15 billion
barrels in oil reserves, more than 1 percent of the estimated world
total. The disputed area itself could hold 850 million barrels,
producing about 200,000 barrels a day and earning about dlrs 2
billion a year, the company believes.
</P>
<P>
   That would not put Guyana on par with nearby Venezuela and
Mexico, which together produce more than 3 million barrels a day.
But it would double the output of the Caribbean's current petroleum
leader, Trinidad and Tobago, and dramatically affect Guyana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 2213 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000704.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senegalese Court Dismisses Charges  </HEADLINE>
By CHIKELUBA KENECHUKU
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) -- A Senegalese court dismissed torture
charges against the exiled Chadian dictator Hissene Habre, saying
Senegal's courts lacked international jurisdiction in the case.
</P>
<P>
   International human rights groups immediately attacked the
ruling, which came just 24 hours after Senegalese President
Abdoulaye Wade removed the judge presiding over the case.
</P>
<P>
   The case was the first time that a former African head of state
has been charged with human rights violations by the court of
another country.
</P>
<P>
   Alioune Tine of Senegal's African Assembly for the Defense of
Human Rights lamented the court's decision in ''the most important
human rights case in Senegal's history.''
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Human Rights Watch, which helped initiate the
criminal action in January, called the decision a ''slap in the
face'' to Habre's victims and said it would protest the
''wrongheaded ruling'' in an appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement announcing the decision, the Dakar Regional
Court said it had no authority to rule in cases of international
scope.
</P>
<P>
   Senegal has no law that specifically authorizes or bars its
courts to try cases involving human rights violations committed in
another country.
</P>
<P>
   Bounta Diallo, a lawyer representing one of Habre's alleged
torture victims, described the ruling as a ''miscarriage of
justice'' and accused Senegal's government of manipulating the
court by replacing Judge Demba Kandji, who first indicted Habre in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Habre ruled the central African nation from 1982 to 1990, and
was backed by the United States and France as a buffer against
Moammar Gadhafi's Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Habre, 57, is a French-trained military tactician from northern
Chad. During his rule, the United States and France gave Chad
millions of dollars in weapons and military equipment.
</P>
<P>
   A commission established by the government of Chad's current
president, Idriss Deby, has accused Habre's regime of 40,000
political murders and 200,000 cases of torture.
</P>
<P>
   Habre has lived in Senegal since he fled Chad in 1990, after his
ouster by Deby.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the case include seven Chadians and one French
woman along with the Chadian Association of Victims of Political
Repression and Crime, which represents 792 alleged victims.
</P>
<P>
   They include Samuel Togoto, 53, who says his hands and legs were
bound behind his back for so long he became temporarily paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   The case was inspired by charges of human rights abuses brought
against Chilean dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet by a Spanish judge.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wade was elected in March, ousting incumbent President
Abdou Diouf, Senegal's courts were the most respected in Africa.
Senegal is a signatory to the U.N. Convention Against Torture,
which obliges states to either prosecute or extradite alleged
torturers who enter their territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-04-00 2234 </TRAILER>
