<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Slope Fires Surge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRAIG, Colo. (AP) -- Two wildfires on Colorado's Western Slope
surged forward Tuesday in conditions so dry that brush burning at
one location was likened to kindling.
</P>
<P>
   A blaze in the Dinosaur National Monument in remote northwestern
Colorado was burning an estimated 9,000 acres, while a smaller fire
about 35 miles southwest of Grand Junction had consumed about 2,500
acres.
</P>
<P>
   Winds were reported at 20 mph at several points and temperatures
ranged into the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   The Dinosaur blaze, which began Monday, was burning mostly on
federal land, said Lynn Barclay, spokeswoman with the Craig
Interagency Dispatch center. No structures were immediately
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was likely to run into natural barriers in some spots,
but firefighters were concerned strong southwesterly winds could
send sparks across the Green River and threaten buildings in the
Browns Park Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, firefighters feared dry conditions and strong
winds would cause the smaller blaze -- burning in kindling-like
pinon, juniper and oak brush -- to spread.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's extremely dry fuel,'' said David Lehmann, spokesman with
the interagency firefighting center in Grand Junction. ''It will be
several days before we get it controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolores River lies between the fire and Gateway, population
300, and normally would be an adequate barrier, he said. ''With
these conditions, it's hard to say.''
</P>
<P>
   A third blaze also was reported, burning across 200 acres about
50 miles southwest of Rangley, near the Utah border in northwestern
Colorado, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In southwestern Wyoming, two wildfires believed to have been
started by lightning had burned about 1,600 acres of shrubs and
grass on public and private land over two days.
</P>
<P>
   The wildfires came less than a month after two blazes burned
about 21,000 acres on the more densely populated eastern side of
the Continental Divide, destroying dozens of homes and other
structures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
